questionTemplates.text:
M: Good morning. What can I do for you?
F: I'd like to buy some New Year's cards.
{a}

W: Hello, is that Steve? I'm stuck in a traffic jam. I'm afraid I can't make it before seven o'clock.
M: Never mind. I'll be here waiting for you.
{a}

M: Have we got everything now?
W: No, I still need to get some eggs, tomatoes and potatoes.
{a}

F: Let's see. Yes. You've got quite a high temperature.
M: I've got a bad headache, too.
{a}

F: Where's Li Lei?
M: He has gone to the reading-room.
{a}

M: It's hot! I wish it would rain and cool off!
W: This isn't usual for November. I don't remember it ever being so hot and dry in November before.
{a}

W: Hi, I'm calling about the three-bedroom house you sell in yesterday's paper. Can you give me more details?
M: Of course.
{a}

M: I have a terrible cold.
W: We have quite a few medications to make you more comfortable.
{a}

W: How did you like the movie?
M: It was a waste of time and money. I wish I had stayed home watching TV.
{a}

W: Do you know that Sam turned down that job offer by a travel agency?
M: Yeah. The hours were convenient, but had he accepted it, he wouldn't have been able to make ends meet.
{a}

M: Professor Smith certainly has a good reputation in the Department of English.
W: A well-deserved one. The same students who fall asleep in discussions and seminars fight for front-row seats in his lectures.
{a}

M: Hello, is Jones in? Can I speak to him?
W: Hold on. He is coming.
{a}

M: What a great singer Justin is! His concert is just awesome. And you'll never regret the money you paid for the ticket.
W: Yeah. Judging by the amount of the applause, everyone was enjoying it.
{a}

W: Shall we meet at a quarter past three?
M: No, let's meet at a quarter to three.
{a}

W: Sir,there's a Mr Miller on the phone who wants to talk to you.
M: I'm busy at the moment. Can you ask him to hold on?Tell him I'll talk with him in a few seconds.
{a}

M: Do you have everything ready?
W: I'm sorry, but I have to buy a pound of sweets and some apples.
{a}

W: Why are you giving me a speeding ticket? I was only going 40.
M: Can't you read? That was 10 M.P.H. over the limit.
{a}

W: There was a storm warning on the radio this morning. Did you happen to be listening?
M: No, but what a shame! I guess we'll have to change our sailing plans. Would you rather play golf or go cycling?
{a}

W: I often go to bed at eleven o'clock. How about you, Jack?
M: That's too late. I usually go to bed an hour earlier than you.
{a}

M: You didn't do well in today's math test. What was the matter?
W: I was in a hurry, and I didn't check over my answers.
{a}

M: Excuse me, is it far from here to hospital?
F: No, not at all. It takes nearly 2 minutes to get there on foot.
{a}

W: What is your dream, Linda?
M: I want to be a nurse.
{a}

M: Er... Hi, could you tell me where electronic products are displayed? I want to see some TVs, digital video cameras, DVD players, that sort of thing.
W: Well. Several countries are displaying electronic products. China's selection is very large this year. You might as well go to the east wing first to take a look at a Chinese booth.
{a}

W: Mary Green is very unlucky. The most terrible things keep happening to her.
M: Yes, if you can trust what she says. But most of her stories are pretty unbelievable in my opinion.
{a}

W: I'm sorry, but the number you dialed is not in service.
M: But that's impossible! I just spoke to him this morning. Please cheek for me.
{a}
